05757nam a22007215i 9781787442535DE-B159720240306014423.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t20182018xxk    fo  d z      eng d  a97817874425357 a10.1515/97817874425352doi  a(DE-B1597)675876  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  axxkcUK 4aPN685 7aLIT0110002bisacsh04a820.935122300aArthurian Literature XXXIV /ced. by David F. Johnson, Elizabeth Archibald.31aWoodbridge, Suffolk : bBoydell and Brewer, c[2018] 1bD.S.Brewer, c[2018] 4c©2018  a1 online resource (177 p.) :b11 b/w illus.  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aArthurian Literature ;v3400tFrontmatter -- tCONTENTS -- tList of Illustrations -- tGeneral Editors’ Foreword -- tList of Contributors -- tI Illusory Ends in Chrétien de Troyes’ Erec et Enide -- tII Who is the Traitor at the Beginning of Sir Gawain and the Green Knight? -- tIII Sir Gawain’s Death and Prophecy in Malory’s Morte Darthur -- tIV Late Medieval Irish Kingship, Egerton 1782, and the Irish Arthurian Romance Eachtra an Mhadra Mhaoil (‘The Story of the Crop-Eared Dog’) -- tV ‘Which I have beholden with most curiouse eyes’: The Lead Cross from Glastonbury abbey -- tVI The Arundel Coronatio Arthuri: A Middle English Sword in the Stone Story from London, College of Arms MS Arundel 58 -- tARUNDEL CORONACIO ARTHURI -- tAPPENDIXES -- tContents of previous volumes0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe continued influence and significance of the legend of Arthur are demonstrated by the articles collected in this volume.The enduring appeal and rich variety of the Arthurian legend are once again manifest here. Chrétien's Erec et Enide features first in a case study of the poet's endings and medieval theories of poetic composition. Next follows an essay that comes to the rather surprising-but- convincing conclusion that the "traitor" spoken of in the opening lines of Sir Gawain and the Green Knight is neither Aeneas nor Antenor, but Paris. Another essay dealing with Sir Gawain, this time in Malory's Morte Darthur, offers among other things an answer to the question of how Gawain knows the exact hour of his death. Few native Irish Arthurian tales have come down to us: a discussion of "The Tale of the Crop-Eared Dog" shows it to be both bizarre and popular, as witnessed by the many manuscripts in which it is preserved. The materiality of the Arthurian legend is represented here by a detailed treatment of the lead cross supposedly found in the grave of King Arthur at Glastonbury Abbey in 1191. Finally, this volume continues Arthurian Literature's tradition of publishing unfamiliar or previously unknown Arthurian texts, in this instance an original Middle English translation of the story of the sword in the stone, from the Old French Merlin. ELIZABETH ARCHIBALD is Professor of English Studies at Durham University, and Principal of StCuthbert's Society; DAVID F. JOHNSON is Professor of English at Florida State University, Tallahassee. Contributors: Lindy Brady, David Carlton, Neil Cartlidge, Nicole Clifton, Oliver Harris, Richard Moll, Rebecca Newby.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aArthurian romancesxHistory and criticism. 0aArthurian romances. 4aArt & Architecture. 4aMedieval Literature. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Medieval.2bisacsh  aFrench romance.  aGawain-poet.  aMalory.  asword.1 aArchibald, Elizabeth, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aBrady, Lindy, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCarlton, David, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCartlidge, Neil M.R., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCartlidge, Neil, econtributor.4ct